{"title_page": "1943 Liberator crash at Whenuapai", "text_new": "{{Infobox Aircraft accident\n|name    = 1943 Liberator crash at Whenuapai \n|image   = Consolidated B-24 artificial horizon.jpg\n|image_size = \n|caption = Gyro horizon from a B-24 Liberator\n|date    = 2 August 1943\n|type    = [[Controlled flight into terrain|Controlled flight into terrain (CFIT)]]\n|occurrence_type = Accident\n|site    = [[New Zealand]]\n|coords  =  {{Coord|36|47|16|S|174|37|49|E|type:airport|display=inline,title}}\n|aircraft_type = [[Consolidated C-87 Liberator Express]]\n|aircraft_name = \n|operator      = [[United Airlines]]\n|tail_number   = 41-24027\n|origin        = [[Whenuapai Aerodrome]]\n|stopover      = \n|stopover0     = \n|stopover1     = \n|stopover2     = \n|stopover3     = \n|last_stopover = \n|destination   = \n|passengers    = 25\n|crew          = 5\n|injuries      = \n|fatalities    = 16\n|survivors     = 14\n}}\n\nThe '''1943 Liberator crash at Whenuapai''' was an aircraft accident in [[New Zealand]] during [[World War II]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10545568|title=Airbus crash not on list of casualties|date=28 November 2008|publisher=New Zealand Herald|accessdate=2009-04-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aviationarchaeology.com/src/AARmonthly/Aug1943O.htm|title=August 1943 USAAF Overseas Accident Reports|publisher=Aviation Archaeological Investigation and Research|accessdate=2009-04-20| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090503181610/http://www.aviationarchaeology.com/src/AARmonthly/Aug1943O.htm| archivedate= 3 May 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> [[TVNZ]] covered the crash during the program ''Secret New Zealand'' in 2003, and posited the accident was covered up, due to concerns of reprisals against POWs.<ref>{{cite book|last=Roscoe|first=Bruce |title=Windows on Japan|publisher=Algora |year=2007|pages=262|isbn=0-87586-491-0|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OxXQ-gn3WgcC&pg=PA262&lpg=PA262| accessdate= 20 April 2009 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nThe [[Consolidated C-87 Liberator Express]] aircraft, owned by the [[USAAF]] and operated using a [[United Airlines]] crew, was transferring Japanese men, women, and children of the [[Consular corps|Consular Corps]], to exchange for Allied [[Prisoner of war|POWs]].<ref name=\"Livingstone1998p115\">{{cite book|last=Livingstone|first=Bob|title=Under the Southern Cross: The B-24 Liberator in the South Pacific|publisher=Turner |year=1998|pages=115|isbn=1-56311-432-1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YbefAXLgqbMC&pg=PA115&lpg=PA115&dq=24027| accessdate= 20 April 2009 <!--DASHBot-->}}</ref> On 2 August 1943, it took off from [[Whenuapai Aerodrome]] runway 04 at 2:20&nbsp;am, with rain and fog conditions at minimums for departure, and quickly passed through low [[stratus cloud|stratus]]. Captain Herschel Laughlin\u2019s [[gyro horizon]] had inadvertently been left caged &ndash; while the instrument displayed level flight, the aircraft entered a steepening bank to the left.<ref name=\"Livingstone1998p115\"/> The crew detected the problem in a few seconds, but as the aircraft was straightening up and levelling out, it hit the ground at about {{convert|322|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}, bounced a few times and exploded. The third bounce threw its first officer, R. John Wisda, out through the canopy; he rolled end over end about {{convert|100|m|ft}} through mud and reeds.<ref name=\"Livingstone1998p115\"/> A medic later found him trying to keep warm near a burning tyre.  R. John Wisda survived the crash.  The major factors of the accident were the lack of a pre-flight checklist, and crew fatigue (126 flying hours in the last 26 days).\n\nThe crash killed three of the five crew (United States nationals), and eleven of the twenty-five passengers (eight Japanese and three Thai nationals).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnzb.govt.nz/DNZB/alt_essayBody.asp?essayID=5P19|title=Pearce, Edna Bertha 1906 - 1995|last=Mackay|first=Jamie|publisher=Dictionary of New Zealand Biography|accessdate=2009-04-20| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090505185731/http://www.dnzb.govt.nz/DNZB/alt_essayBody.asp?essayID=5P19| archivedate= 5 May 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> Two additional passengers died later from injuries.<ref name=\"Livingstone1998p115\"/> {{Ship|TSS|Wahine}} took the surviving internees from Wellington to Sydney three months later.<ref>{{cite book|last=King|first=John|title=Aviation Accidents and Disasters|publisher=Grantham House|location=Wellington|year=1995|series=New Zealand Tragedies|pages=136|isbn=1-86934-042-6}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Liberator: The Facts|last=Bevan|first=E. Denys|date=4 November 1991|publisher=The Listener}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Letter|last=Sim|first=J. W.|date=November 1988|publisher=New Zealand Wings}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Aviation accidents and incidents in 1943}}\n\n{{United Airlines}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Liberator crash at Whenuapai, 1943}}\n[[Category:1943 in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents caused by pilot error]]\n[[Category:1940s in Auckland]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:Aviation accidents and incidents in 1943]]\n[[Category:United Airlines accidents and incidents]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Aircraft accident\n|name    = 1943 Liberator crash at Whenuapai \n|image   = Consolidated B-24 artificial horizon.jpg\n|image_size = \n|caption = Gyro horizon from a B-24 Liberator\n|date    = 2 August 1943\n|type    = [[Controlled flight into terrain|Controlled flight into terrain (CFIT)]]\n|occurrence_type = Accident\n|site    = [[New Zealand]]\n|coords  =  {{Coord|36|47|16|S|174|37|49|E|type:airport|display=inline,title}}\n|aircraft_type = [[Consolidated C-87 Liberator Express]]\n|aircraft_name = \n|operator      = [[United Airlines]]\n|tail_number   = 41-24027\n|origin        = [[Whenuapai Aerodrome]]\n|stopover      = \n|stopover0     = \n|stopover1    