;am, with rain and fog conditions at minimums for departure, and quickly passed through low [[stratus cloud|stratus]]. Captain Herschel Laughlin\u2019s [[gyro horizon]] had inadvertently been left caged &ndash; while the instrument displayed level flight, the aircraft entered a steepening bank to the left.<ref name=\"Livingstone1998p115\"/> The crew detected the problem in a few seconds, but as the aircraft was straightening up and levelling out, it hit the ground at about {{convert|322|km/h|mph|abbr=on}}, bounced a few times and exploded. The third bounce threw its first officer, R. John Wisda, out through the canopy; he rolled end over end about {{convert|100|m|ft}} through mud and reeds.<ref name=\"Livingstone1998p115\"/> A medic later found him trying to keep warm near a burning tyre. The major factors of the accident were the lack of a pre-flight checklist, and crew fatigue (126 flying hours in the last 26 days).\n\nThe crash killed three of the five crew (United States nationals), and eleven of the twenty-five passengers (eight Japanese and three Thai nationals).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dnzb.govt.nz/DNZB/alt_essayBody.asp?essayID=5P19|title=Pearce, Edna Bertha 1906 - 1995|last=Mackay|first=Jamie|publisher=Dictionary of New Zealand Biography|accessdate=2009-04-20| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090505185731/http://www.dnzb.govt.nz/DNZB/alt_essayBody.asp?essayID=5P19| archivedate= 5 May 2009 | url-status= live}}</ref> Two additional passengers died later from injuries.<ref name=\"Livingstone1998p115\"/> {{Ship|TSS|Wahine}} took the surviving internees from Wellington to Sydney three months later.<ref>{{cite book|last=King|first=John|title=Aviation Accidents and Disasters|publisher=Grantham House|location=Wellington|year=1995|series=New Zealand Tragedies|pages=136|isbn=1-86934-042-6}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Liberator: The Facts|last=Bevan|first=E. Denys|date=4 November 1991|publisher=The Listener}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Letter|last=Sim